PCL102H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course introduces students to the processes and strategies for discovering new drugs with a special focus on current and emerging approaches for the rational design of drugs that are both effective and safe.
PCL102H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Rebecca Laposa, rebecca.laposa@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL200H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Lectures introduce students to prescribed and illicit drugs that affect the brain. Lectures cover drug pharmacology and explain how drugs alter mood, perception, cognition, and arousal by affecting different aspects of brain function. The societal impact of these prescribed and illicit drugs is also discussed
PCL200H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Amy Ramsey, a.ramsey@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL201H1-S-20179.courseTitle: Introduction to Pharmacology and Pharmacokinetic Principles
PCL201H1-S-20179.courseDescription: A general introduction to the principles of pharmacology and pharmacokinetics. Topics include chemical (drug) absorption, distribution, biotransformation, elimination; the calculation of dosages and pharmacokinetic parameters, variability in drug response, adverse drug reactions and special interest topics.
PCL201H1-S-20179.corequisite: Recommended Co-requisites: BIO230H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1), CHM247H1/CHM249H1, PSL300H1/PSL301H1
PCL201H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions:
Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL297H1-F-20179.courseDescription: A formal opportunity to gain hands-on experience and develop their skills within a research laboratory setting. Students will have a chance to become familiar and efficient at good lab practices, develop critical thinking and evaluation skills while applying their knowledge and developing trouble shooting skills to practical research questions. This course is Pass/Fail. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PCL297H1-F-20179.prerequisite: None; Permission of Faculty Supervisor and Departmental Undergraduate Coordinator required.
PCL297H1-F-20179.recommendedPreparation: Completion of at least first year of Life Sciences program.

PCL302H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Topics include biological action of drugs on membranes, enzymes, receptors, neural and hormonal systems, transmission and modulation.
PCL302H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Jane Mitchell, jane.mitchell@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL345H1-S-20179.courseDescription: Lecturers use their own research to demonstrate how they approach a biological question. The lectures emphasize why one approach is chosen over other possible approaches, and explain the strengths and limitations of techniques. Following the one-hour lecture there is an interactive discussion of the experimental approach covered in the lecture.
PCL345H1-S-20179.prerequisite: BCH210H1; completion of at least 10 FCE
PCL345H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Ana Andreazza, ana.andreazza@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL362H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Toxicological problems encountered in animals and humans; biochemical mechanisms and clinical factors of toxicological significance; models of drug-related diseases.
PCL362H1-F-20179.prerequisite: BCH210H1, BIO230H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1), CHM247H1/CHM249H1, PCL201H1 or Permission of the Course Coordinator
PCL362H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Peter Wells, pg.wells@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL366H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Through practical hands-on laboratory experiments and tutorials, students will be introduced to some basic experimental techniques that are used within pharmacology and toxicology research. This course results from the splitting of PCL365Y and PCL471Y and provides students an opportunity to develop introductory and basic laboratory skills.
PCL366H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Anita Hamadanizadeh, anita.hamadanizadeh@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL376H1-F-20179.courseTitle: Experimental Design and Data Analysis for Pharmacology and Toxicology
PCL376H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This course includes lectures focused on experimental design and the analysis of pharmacological and toxicological data. Topics include: principles of experimental design, data analysis and statistical tests appropriate for each type, use of computing statistical packages, analysis of dose-response and time-response curves and analysis of receptor binding assays. Practical applications and problem sets will be taken up in class and in tutorials.
PCL376H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Laurel Duquette, laurel.duquette@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions

PCL389H1-F-20179.courseTitle: Understanding the Role of Pharmacology and Toxicology in Society
PCL389H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This service learning course explores issues surrounding the effects that pharmaceuticals and chemicals have in society. Specifically, it integrates pharmacology and toxicology with social, health and political issues as they relate to drug abuse and addiction. Students are required to interact and work with community partners during the semester (approx 20hrs). Classroom discussions will integrate community experiences with lecture material.
PCL389H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL402H1-F-20179.courseTitle: Pharmacology and Toxicology in Drug Development
PCL402H1-F-20179.courseDescription: This course provides the basic principles of drug development, with a primary focus on the application of fundamental principles of pharmacology and toxicology to the design and conduct of early phase clinical trials. This is the phase of the drug development process where much of the innovation and science occurs.
PCL402H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Rebecca Laposa, rebecca.laposa@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL461H1-S-20179.courseDescription: Advanced laboratory exercises and discussions through tutorials and presentations in selected areas of pharmacology. Enrollment in this course is generally restricted to students enrolled in the Pharmacology Specialist and Pharmacology and Biomedical Toxicology Specialist programs.
PCL461H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Anita Hamadanizadeh, anita.hamadanizadeh@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL465H1-S-20179.courseDescription: An advanced hands-on laboratory course exploring a wide variety of modern experimental techniques currently utilized in toxicology. This course will provide the experimental theory of how the techniques work and their advantages and disadvantages, while additionally allowing students to perform these techniques in the process of addressing toxicological problems. Enrollment in this course is generally restricted to students enrolled in the Biomedical Toxicology Specialist, Pharmacology and Biomedical Toxicology Specialist, and Environment and Toxicology Specialist programs.
PCL465H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Please note that this course will NOT be offered in January 2018 if there are fewer than 12 students enrolled by January 3rd, 2018. Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Anita Hamadanizadeh, anita.hamadanizadeh@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL469H1-S-20179.courseDescription: A culmination of pharmacological principles discussing concepts of drug properties and their interactions within the body. The mechanism of action, pharmacological properties including clinical use and adverse effects of drugs acting on the autonomic nervous systems, cardiovascular, renal, respiratory, gastrointestinal and endocrine systems will be examined. Critical evaluation of primary literature and examination of clinical problem-based case studies will be integrated with lecture material through small group sessions.
PCL469H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL470H1-F-20179.courseDescription: A culmination of pharmacological principles discussing concepts of drug properties and their interactions within the body. The mechanism of action, pharmacological properties including clinical use and adverse effects of drugs acting on the central nervous systems and immunological system; antimicrobial and cancer chemotherapeutic agents as well as the potential therapeutic use of endogenous/herbal compounds will be examined. Critical evaluation of primary literature and examination of clinical problem-based case studies will be integrated with lecture material through small group sessions.
PCL470H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Ali Salahpour, ali.salahpour@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL472Y1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course affords students an opportunity for hands-on research experience in a laboratory or applied pharmacology setting. Students will work under the supervision of a faculty member and will submit a final written report and oral presentation. Enrollment is limited and requires permission from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology. It is the students responsibility to secure a placement with an approved supervisor before the course begins (a list of potential supervisors can be obtained from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology). Students will be registered in the course once their ballot form (obtained from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology) is signed by an approved supervisor and approved by the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology. Students are expected to spend approximately 200 hours towards this project but this will be project/supervisor dependent. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PCL472Y1-S-20179.prerequisite: PCL201H1, PCL302H1, PCL366H1, PCL376H1 and permission of Department

PCL473Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: This course explores several contemporary topics in biomedical and environmental toxicology with emphasis on how chemicals affect human health. Lectures cover principles of toxicology, the mechanisms of toxicity of a wide variety of toxic agents and the associated toxicities, methodologies used to examine chemical toxicities, risk assessment, and the applications of toxicology. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PCL473Y1-Y-20179.prerequisite: BCH210H1, PCL201H1, PCL302H1, PCL362H1 or Permission of the Course Coordinator
PCL473Y1-Y-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Peter McPherson, peter.mcpherson@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL475Y1-Y-20179.courseDescription: Major neuro-psychiatric disease syndromes: clinical pathology and neuronal abnormalities; CNS drugs: theories and mechanisms of action.
PCL475Y1-Y-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Mac Burnham, mac.burnham@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL477H1-F-20179.courseTitle: The DNA Damage Response in Pharmacology and Toxicology
PCL477H1-F-20179.courseDescription: Many anticancer drugs and environmental agents exert their cytotoxic effects through DNA damage. This course explores specific pharmacological and toxicological agents that damage DNA and discusses how mammalian cells respond to this DNA damage.
PCL477H1-F-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Peter McPherson, peter.mcpherson@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL481H1-S-20179.courseTitle: The Molecular and Biochemical Basis of Toxicology
PCL481H1-S-20179.courseDescription: The biochemical principles and molecular mechanisms underlying the toxicity of drugs and foreign agents. The sequence of events at the molecular level leading to impairment of cell function and the factors which determine and affect toxicity.
PCL481H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Denis Grant, denis.grant@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL486H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course will expand on both classical and cutting edge pharmacological strategies proposed to mitigate the consequences of altered signal transduction in cancer. Students will have the opportunity to develop knowledge on these molecular events and how they can be targeted to improve clinical outcomes. Students will integrate lecture material with assigned readings and assignments.
PCL486H1-S-20179.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Leonardo Salmena, leonardo.salmena@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL491H1-S-20179.courseDescription: This course will examine the practical and experimental aspects of clinical pharmacology and toxicology. Through practical applications and experiments, students will develop their knowledge in Good Laboratory Practice/Good CLinical Practice, critical evaluation and analysis skills through: performing pharmacokinetic experiments (evaluating Vd, half-life, and clearance); examining case studies and primary literature in regards to drug-drug interactions and adverse drug reactions.  This elective course can apply towards their program requirements in our Specialist and Major streams and will only be available to fourth year students. The course will meet a need expanding students comprehension in clinical pharmaoclogy and pharmacokinetics in a hands-on practical and advnace manner. Students will be evaluated on both written and oral communication skills, team work as well as data analysis and interpretation and critical thinking skills.
PCL491H1-S-20179.prerequisite: PCL201H1, PCL302H1, at least 15 FCE and completion of upper level laboratory course.
PCL491H1-S-20179.recommendedPreparation: PCL469H1, PCL470H1 or PCL473Y1. Completion of an upper level laboratory course (PCL366H1, PSL372H1, BCH370H1)
